# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fire-safety-evaluation-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety-evaluation-system] The **Fire Safety Evaluation System** (FSES) is a system used in the United States to evaluate the overall level of a building's fire safety.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety-evaluation-system] FSES applies to health care, prisons and jails, offices, laboratory buildings, and overnight accommodations in National Parks.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety-evaluation-system] FSES values are provided in the National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) Standard 101A, *Guide on Alternative Approaches to Life Safety*.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety-evaluation-system] A FSES evaluation defines the relative impact of a deficiency or proposed improvement to the building.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety-evaluation-system] It also provides a means of comparing the effectiveness of proposed improvements by producing a comparative baseline and readily shows the relative gain in fire safety for proposed improvements.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety-evaluation-system] Fire sprinklers have an extensive impact on fire safety and are therefore allotted a high value in the FSES.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire safety measures include those that are planned during the construction of a building or implemented in structures that are already standing and those that are taught or provided to occupants of the building.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Threats to fire safety are commonly referred to as fire hazards.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] A fire hazard may include a situation that increases the likelihood of a fire or may impede escape in the event a fire occurs.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire safety is often a component of building safety.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Those who inspect buildings for violations of the fire codes, and visit schools to educate children on fire safety topics, are fire department members known as *Fire Prevention Officers*.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] The Chief Fire Prevention Officer or Chief of Fire Prevention will normally train newcomers to the Fire Prevention Division and may also conduct inspections or make presentations.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire safety policies apply at the construction of a building and throughout its operating life.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Building codes are enacted by local, sub-national, or national governments to ensure such features as adequate fire exits, signage, and construction details such as fire stops and fire rated doors, windows, and walls.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire safety is also an objective of electrical codes to prevent overheating of wiring or equipment, and to protect from ignition by electrical faults.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire codes regulate such requirements as the maximum occupancy for buildings such as theatres or restaurants, for example.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire codes may require portable fire extinguishers within a building, or may require permanently installed fire detection and suppression equipment such as a fire sprinkler system and a fire alarm system.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Local authorities charged with fire safety may conduct regular inspections for such items as usable fire exit and proper exit signage, functional fire extinguishers of the correct type in accessible places, and proper storage and handling of flammable materials.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Depending on local regulations, a fire inspection may result in a notice of required action, or closing of a building until it can be put into compliance with fire code requirements.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Owners and managers of a building may implement additional fire policies.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] For example, an industrial site may designate and train particular employees as a fire fighting force.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Managers must ensure buildings comply with fire evacuation regulations, and that building features such as spray fireproofing remains undamaged.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire policies may be in place to dictate training and awareness of occupants and users of the building to avoid obvious mistakes, such as the propping open of fire doors.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Buildings, especially institutions such as schools, may conduct fire drills at regular intervals throughout the year.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Beyond individual buildings, other elements of fire safety policies may include technologies such as wood coatings, education and prevention, preparedness measures, wildfire detection and suppression, and ensuring geographic coverage of local and sufficient fire extinguishing capacities.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] In the United States, the fire code (also fire prevention code or fire safety code) is a model code adopted by the state or local jurisdiction and enforced by fire prevention officers within municipal fire departments.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] It is a set of rules prescribing minimum requirements to prevent fire and explosion hazards arising from storage, handling, or use of dangerous materials, or from other specific hazardous conditions.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] The fire code is aimed primarily at preventing fires, ensuring that necessary training and equipment will be on hand, and that the original design basis of the building, including the basic plan set out by the architect, is not compromised.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] The fire code also addresses inspection and maintenance requirements of various fire protection equipment in order to maintain optimal active fire protection and passive fire protection measures.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Sections may establish the requirements for obtaining permits and specific precautions required to remain in compliance with a permit.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] For example, a fireworks exhibition may require an application to be filed by a licensed pyrotechnician, providing the information necessary for the issuing authority to determine whether safety requirements can be met.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Once a permit is issued, the same authority (or another delegated authority) may inspect the site and monitor safety during the exhibition, with the power to halt operations, when unapproved practices are seen or when unforeseen hazards arise.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Most U.S. fire departments have fire safety education programs.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire prevention programs may include distribution of smoke detectors, visiting schools to review key topics with the students and implementing nationally recognized programs such as NFPAS "Risk Watch" and "Learn not to burn".
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Other programs or props can be purchased by fire departments or community organizations.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] These are usually entertaining and designed to capture children's attention and relay important messages.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Props include those that are mostly auditory, such as puppets and robots.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] The prop is visually stimulating but the safety message is only transmitted orally.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Other props are more elaborate, access more senses and increase the learning factor.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] They mix audio messages and visual cues with hands-on interaction.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Examples of these include mobile trailer safety houses and tabletop hazard house simulators.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Some fire prevention software is also being developed to identify hazards in a home.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] All programs tend to mix messages of general injury prevention, safety, fire prevention, and escape in case of fire.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] In most cases the fire department representative is regarded as the expert and is expected to present information in a manner that is appropriate for each age group.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] According to the United States Fire Administration, the very young and the elderly are considered to be "at risk" populations.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] These groups represent approximately 33% of the population.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire safety has been highlighted in relation to global supply chain management.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Sedex, the Supplier Ethical Data Exchange, a collaborative platform for sharing ethical supply chain data, and Verité, Inc., a Massachusetts-based supply chain investigatory NGO, issued a briefing in August 2013 which highlighted the significance of this issue.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] The briefing recommended that buyers seek greater visibility of fire safety and other risks across the supply chain and identify opportunities to improve standards: "buyers can encourage change through more responsible and consistent practices".
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] A **fire safety plan** is required by all North American national, state and provincial fire codes based on building use or occupancy types.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Generally, the owner of the building is responsible for the preparation of a fire safety plan.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Buildings with elaborate emergency systems may require the assistance of a fire protection consultant.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] After the plan has been prepared, it must be submitted to the Chief Fire Official or authority having jurisdiction for approval.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Once approved, the owner is responsible for implementing the fire safety plan and training all staff in their duties.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] It is also the owner's responsibility to ensure that all visitors and staff are informed of what to do in case of fire.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] During a fire emergency, a copy of the approved fire safety plan must be available for the responding fire department's use.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] In the United Kingdom, a fire safety plan is called a fire risk assessment.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire safety plans are a useful tool for fire fighters to have because they allow them to know critical information about a building that they may have to go into.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Using this, fire fighters can locate and avoid potential dangers such as hazardous material (hazmat) storage areas and flammable chemicals.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] In addition to this, fire safety plans can also provide specialized information that, in the case of a hospital fire, can provide information about the location of things like the nuclear medicine ward.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] In addition to this, fire safety plans also greatly improve the safety of fire fighters.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] According to FEMA, 16 percent of all fire fighter deaths in 2002 occurred due to a structural collapse or because the fire fighter got lost.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire safety plans can outline any possible structural hazards, as well as give the fire fighter knowledge of where he is in the building.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] In North America alone, there are around 8 million buildings that legally require a fire safety plan, be it due to provincial or state law.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Not having a fire safety plan for buildings which fit the fire code occupancy type can result in a fine, and they are required for all buildings, such as commercial, industrial, assembly, etc.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] As previously stated, a copy of the approved fire safety plan shall be available for the responding fire department.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Up until now, all fire plans were stored in paper form in the fire department.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] The problem with this is that sorting and storing these plans is a challenge, and it is difficult for people to update their fire plans.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] As a result, only half of the required buildings have fire plans, and of those, only around 10 percent are up-to-date.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] This problem has been solved through the introduction of digital fire plans.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] These fire plans are stored in a database and can be accessed wirelessly on site by firefighters and are much simpler for building owners to update.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Fire is one of the biggest threats to property with losses adding up to billions of dollars in damages every year.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] In 2019 alone, the total amount of property damage resulting from fire was $14.8 billion in the United States.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Insurance companies in the United States are not only responsible for financially covering fire loss but are also responsible for managing risk associated with it.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Most commercial insurance companies hire a risk control specialist whose primary job is to survey property to ensure compliance with NFPA standards, assess the current risk level of the property, and make recommendations to reduce the probability of fire loss.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-safety] Careers in property risk management continue to grow and have been projected to grow 4 to 8% from 2018 to 2028 in the United States.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] A **fire sprinkler** or **sprinkler head** is the component of a fire sprinkler system that discharges water when the effects of a fire have been detected, such as when a predetermined temperature has been exceeded.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Fire sprinklers are extensively used worldwide, with over 40 million sprinkler heads fitted each year.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] In buildings protected by properly designed and maintained fire sprinklers, over 99% of fires were controlled by fire sprinklers alone.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] In 1812, British inventor Sir William Congreve patented a manual sprinkler system using perforated pipes along the ceiling.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] When someone noticed a fire, a valve outside the building could be opened to send water through the pipes.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] It was not until a short time later that, as a result of a large furniture factory that repeatedly burned down, Hiram Stevens Maxim was consulted on how to prevent a recurrence and invented the first automatic fire sprinkler.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] It would douse the areas that were on fire and report the fire to the fire station.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Maxim was unable to sell the idea elsewhere, though when the patent expired, the idea was used.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Martin was awarded a patent for improvement to the fire extinguisher which involved the use of pipes to carry water upwards and valves in the ceiling acting as sprinklers to extinguish fires in buildings.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Parmalee of New Haven, Connecticut, created and installed the first automatic fire sprinkler system, using solder that melted in a fire to unplug holes in the otherwise sealed water pipes.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] He was the president of Mathusek Piano Works, and invented his sprinkler system in response to exorbitantly high insurance rates.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Parmelee patented his idea and had great success with it in the U.S., calling his invention the "automatic fire extinguisher".
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] He then traveled to Europe to demonstrate his method to stop a building fire before total destruction.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Parmelee's invention did not get as much attention as he had planned, as most people could not afford to install a sprinkler system.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Once he realized this, he turned his efforts to educating insurance companies about his system.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] He explained that the sprinkler system would reduce the loss ratio, and thus save money for the insurance companies.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] He knew that he could never succeed in obtaining contracts from the business owners to install his system unless he could ensure for them a reasonable return in the form of reduced premiums.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] In this connection, he was able to enlist the interest of two men, who both had connections in the insurance industry.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The first of was Major Hesketh, a cotton spinner in a large business in Bolton who was also chairman of the Bolton Cotton Trades Mutual Insurance Company.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The directors of this company and its secretary, Peter Kevan, took an interest in Parmelee's early experiments.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Hesketh got Parmelee his first order for sprinkler installations in the cotton spinning mills of John Stones & Company, at Astley Bridge, Bolton.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] This was followed soon afterwards by an order from the Alexandra Mills, owned by John Butler of the same town.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Although Parmelee got two sales through its efforts, the Bolton Cotton Trades Mutual Insurance Company was not a very big company outside of its local area.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] He found this influence in James North Lane, the manager of the Mutual Fire Insurance Corporation of Manchester.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] This company was founded in 1870 by the Textile Manufacturers' Associations of Lancashire and Yorkshire as a protest against high insurance rates.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] They had a policy of encouraging risk management and more particularly the use of the most up-to-date and scientific apparatus for extinguishing fires.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Even though he put tremendous effort and time into educating the masses on his sprinkler system, by 1883 only about 10 factories were protected by the Parmelee sprinkler.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Back in the U.S., Frederick Grinnell, who was manufacturing the Parmelee sprinkler, designed the more effective Grinnell sprinkler.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] He increased sensitivity by removing the fusible joint from all contact with the water, and, by seating a valve in the center of a flexible diaphragm, he relieved the low-fusing soldered joint of the strain of water pressure.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] By this means, the valve seat was forced against the valve by the water pressure, producing a self-closing action.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The greater the water pressure, the tighter the valve.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The flexible diaphragm had a further and more important function.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] It caused the valve and its seat to move outwards simultaneously until the solder joint was completely severed.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Grinnell got a patent for his version of the sprinkler system.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] He also took his invention to Europe, where it was a much bigger success than the Parmelee version.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Eventually, the Parmelee system was withdrawn, opening the path for Grinnell and his invention.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Fire sprinkler application and installation guidelines, and overall fire sprinkler system design guidelines are provided by the National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) 13, (NFPA) 13D, and (NFPA) 13R and enforced by local jurisdictions.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Certain states, including California, Pennsylvania and Illinois, require sprinklers in at least some new residential construction.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Fire sprinklers can be automatic or open orifice.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Automatic fire sprinklers use a fusible element that activates at a predetermined temperature.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The fusible element either melts or has a frangible liquid-containing glass bulb that breaks, causing the water pressure in the fire sprinkler piping to push a plug out of the sprinkler orifice, resulting in water spraying from the orifice.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The water stream strikes a deflector that forms the water into a spray pattern designed in support of the goals of the sprinkler type (i.e., control or suppression).
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Modern sprinkler heads are designed to direct spray downwards.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Spray nozzles are available to provide spray in various directions and patterns.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The majority of automatic fire sprinklers operate individually in a fire.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Contrary to motion picture representation, the entire sprinkler system does not activate at the same time, unless the system is a special deluge type.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Open orifice sprinklers are only used in water spray systems or deluge sprinklers systems.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] They are identical to the automatic sprinkler on which they are based, with the heat-sensitive operating element removed.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Automatic fire sprinklers utilizing frangible bulbs follow a standardized color-coding convention indicating their operating temperature.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Activation temperatures correspond to the type of hazard against which the sprinkler system protects.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The 2002 edition of the NFPA #13 standard, section 3.6.1 defines quick response sprinklers as having a response time index (RTI) of 50 (meter-seconds)1/2 or less.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] RTI is a measure of how thermally responsive the heat-responsive element of the sprinkler is, measured as the time needed to raise the temperature of the sprinkler bulb to 63% of the temperature of the hot air stream times the square root of the velocity of the air stream.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The term quick response refers to the listing of the entire sprinkler (including spacing, density and location) not just the fast responding releasing element.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Many standard response sprinklers, such as extended coverage ordinary hazard (ECOH) sprinklers, have fast responding (low thermal mass elements) in order to pass their fire tests.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Quick response sprinklers are available with standard spray deflectors, but they are also available with extended coverage deflectors.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Each closed-head sprinkler is held closed by either a heat-sensitive glass bulb (see below) or a two-part metal link held together with a fusible alloy such as Wood's metal and other alloys with similar compositions.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The glass bulb or link applies pressure to a pipe cap which acts as a plug which prevents water from flowing until the ambient temperature around the sprinkler reaches the design activation temperature of the individual sprinkler.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Because each sprinkler activates independently when the predetermined heat level is reached, the number of sprinklers that operate is limited to only those near the fire, thereby maximizing the available water pressure over the point of fire origin.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The bulb breaks as a result of the thermal expansion of the liquid inside the bulb.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The time it takes before a bulb breaks is dependent on the temperature.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Below the design temperature, it does not break, and above the design temperature, it breaks, taking less time to break as temperature increases above the design threshold.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The response time is expressed as a response time index (RTI), which typically has values between 35 and 250 m½s½, where a low value indicates a fast response.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Under standard testing procedures (135 °C air at a velocity of 2.5 m/s), a 68 °C sprinkler bulb will break within 7 to 33 seconds, depending on the RTI.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The RTI can also be specified in imperial units, where 1 ft½s½ is equivalent to 0.55 m½s½.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] The sensitivity of a sprinkler can be negatively affected if the thermal element has been painted.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] From Table 6.2.5.1 NFPA13 2007 Edition indicates the maximum ceiling temperature, nominal operating temperature of the sprinkler, color of the bulb or link and the temperature classification.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] ESFR (early suppression fast response) refers to both a concept and a type of sprinkler.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] ESFR sprinkler heads were developed in the 1980s to take advantage of the latest fast-response fire sprinkler technology to provide fire suppression of specific high-challenge fire hazards.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/fire-sprinkler] Prior to the introduction of these sprinklers, protection systems were designed to control fires until the arrival of the fire department.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] The **National Fire Protection Association** (**NFPA**) is a U.S.-based international nonprofit organization devoted to eliminating death, injury, property damage, and economic loss due to fire, electrical, and related hazards.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] As of 2025, the NFPA claims to have 50,000 members and 10,000 volunteers working with the organization through its 250 technical committees.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] In 1895, a Committee on Automatic Sprinkler Protection was formed in Massachusetts by men affiliated with several fire insurance companies and a pipe manufacturer to develop a uniform standard for the design and installation of fire sprinkler systems.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] At the time, there were nine such standards in effect within 100 miles (160 km) of Boston, Massachusetts, and such diversity was causing great difficulties for plumbers working in the New England region.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] The next year, the committee published its initial report on a uniform standard and later formed the NFPA in late 1896.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] The committee's initial report evolved into NFPA 13, *Standard for the Installation of Sprinkler Systems,* the most widely used fire sprinkler standard.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] Around 1904, the NFPA began expanding its membership from affiliates of fire insurance companies to many other organizations and individuals, and also broadened its mission beyond promulgating fire sprinkler standards.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] The association publishes more than 300 consensus codes and standards intended to minimize the possibility and effects of fire and other risks.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] The codes and standards are administered by more than 250 technical committees consisting of approximately 9,000 volunteers.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] A children's book about Sparky by Don Hoffman was published in 2011.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] He serves as the spokesdog for Fire Prevention Week each October in the United States and Canada.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-fire-protection-association] NFPA sponsored a NASCAR O'Reilly Auto Parts Series race at the Martinsville Speedway on March 28, 2026, called the NFPA 250.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] A **national park** is a nature park designated for conservation purposes because of unparalleled national natural, historic, or cultural significance.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] It is an area of natural, semi-natural, or developed land that is protected and owned by a government.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Although governments hold different standards for national park designation, the conservation of 'wild nature' for posterity and as a symbol of national pride is a common motivation for the continued protection of all national parks around the world.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] National parks are almost always accessible to the public.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Usually national parks are developed, owned and managed by national governments, though in some countries with federal or devolved forms of government, "national parks" may be the responsibility of subnational, regional, or local authorities.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The United States established Yellowstone National Park, the first "public park or pleasuring-ground for the benefit and enjoyment of the people", in 1872.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Although Yellowstone was not officially termed a "national park" at the time, in practice it is widely held to be the first and oldest national park in the world.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The Tobago Main Ridge Forest Reserve (in what is now Trinidad and Tobago; established in 1776) and the area surrounding Bogd Khan Uul Mountain (Mongolia, 1778), which were restricted from cultivation to protect surrounding farmland, are considered the oldest legally protected areas.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Parks Canada, established on May 19, 1911, is the world's oldest national park service.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) and its World Commission on Protected Areas (WCPA) have defined "National Park" as its *Category II* type of protected areas.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] According to the IUCN, 6,555 national parks worldwide met its criteria in 2006.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] IUCN is still discussing the parameters of defining a national park.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The largest national park in the world meeting the IUCN definition is the Northeast Greenland National Park, which was established in 1974 and is 972,000 km2 (375,000 sq mi) in area.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In 1971, these criteria were further expanded upon leading to more clear and defined benchmarks to evaluate a national park.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In Canada, there are both national parks operated by the federal government and provincial or territorial parks operated by the provincial and territorial governments, although nearly all are still national parks by the IUCN definition.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In many countries, including Indonesia, the Netherlands, and the United Kingdom, national parks do not adhere to the IUCN definition, while some areas which adhere to the IUCN definition are not designated as national parks.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] As many countries do not adhere to the IUCN definition, the term "national park" may be used loosely.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In the United Kingdom, and in some other countries such as Taiwan, a "national park" simply describes a general area that is relatively undeveloped, scenic, and attracts tourists, with some form of planning restrictions to ensure it maintains those characteristics.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] There may be substantial human settlements within the bounds of a national park.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Conversely, parks that meet the criteria may be not be referred to as "national parks".
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Terms like "preserve" or "reserve" may be used instead.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In 1810, the English poet William Wordsworth described the Lake District as a "sort of national property, in which every man has a right and interest who has an eye to perceive and a heart to enjoy".
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The painter George Catlin, in his travels through the American West, wrote during the 1830s that Native Americans in the United States might be preserved "(by some great protecting policy of government) ... in a *magnificent park* ...
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] It was known as Hot Springs Reservation, but no legal authority was established.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Federal control of the area was not clearly established until 1877.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The work of important leaders who fought for animal and land conservation were essential in the development of legal action.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Some of these leaders include President Abraham Lincoln, Laurance Rockefeller, President Theodore Roosevelt, John Muir, and First Lady Lady Bird Johnson to name a few.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] John Muir is today referred to as the "Father of the National Parks" due to his work in Yosemite.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] He published two influential articles in *The Century Magazine*, which formed the basis for the subsequent legislation.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] President Abraham Lincoln signed an Act of Congress on 1 July 1864, ceding the Yosemite Valley and the Mariposa Grove of giant sequoias (later becoming Yosemite National Park) to the state of California.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] According to this bill, private ownership of the land in this area was no longer possible.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The state of California was designated to manage the park for "public use, resort, and recreation".
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Leases were permitted for up to ten years and the proceeds were to be used for conservation and improvement.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] A public discussion followed this first legislation of its kind and there was a heated debate over whether the government had the right to create parks.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The perceived mismanagement of Yosemite by the Californian state was the reason why Yellowstone was put under national control at its establishment six years later.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In 1872, Yellowstone National Park was established as the United States' first national park, being also the world's first national park.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In some European and Asian countries, however, national protection and nature reserves already existed - though typically as game reserves and recreational grounds set aside for royalty, such as a part of the Forest of Fontainebleau (France, 1861).
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Yellowstone was part of a federally governed territory.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] With no state government that could assume stewardship of the land, the federal government took on direct responsibility for the park, the official first national park of the United States.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The combined effort and interest of conservationists, politicians and the Northern Pacific Railroad ensured the passage of enabling legislation by the United States Congress to create Yellowstone National Park.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Theodore Roosevelt and his group of conservationists, the Boone and Crockett Club, were active campaigners and were highly influential in convincing fellow Republicans and big business to back the bill.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Yellowstone National Park soon played a pivotal role in the conservation of these national treasures, as it was suffering at the hands of poachers and others who stood at the ready to pillage what they could from the area.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Theodore Roosevelt and his newly formed Boone and Crockett Club successfully took the lead in protecting Yellowstone National Park from this plight, resulting in laws designed to conserve the natural resources in Yellowstone and other parks under the Government's purview.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] American Pulitzer Prize-winning author Wallace Stegner wrote: "National parks are the best idea we ever had.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The first area to use "national park" in its creation legislation was the U.S.'s Mackinac National Park, in 1875.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Following the idea established in Yellowstone and Mackinac, there soon followed parks in other nations.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In Australia, what is now Royal National Park was established just south of Sydney, Colony of New South Wales, on 26 April 1879, becoming the world's second official national park.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Since Mackinac lost its national park status, the Royal National Park is, by some considerations, the second oldest national park now in existence.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Banff National Park became Canada's first national park in 1885.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] New Zealand established Tongariro National Park in 1887.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Argentina became the third country in the Americas to create a national park system, with the creation of the Nahuel Huapi National Park in 1934, through the initiative of Francisco Moreno.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In Europe, the first national parks were a set of nine in Sweden in 1909, following the passing of a Riksdag law on national parks that year.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Switzerland became the second European nation with the founding of the Swiss National Park in 1914.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In 1971, Lahemaa National Park in Estonian SSR became the first area to be designated a national park in the former Soviet Union.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Africa's first national park was established in 1925 when king Albert I of Belgium designated an area in the east of what was then his personal domain of Congo Free State, now Democratic Republic of Congo as the Albert National Park, later renamed Virunga National Park.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In 1926, the government of South Africa designated Kruger National Park as the nation's first national park, although it was an expansion and reorganization of the earlier government protected Sabie Game Reserve, established in 1898 by President Paul Kruger of the old South African Republic.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] After World War II, national parks were founded all over the world.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The United Kingdom designated its first national park, Peak District National Park, in 1951.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] This followed perhaps 70 years of pressure for greater public access to the landscape.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] By the end of the decade a further nine national parks had been designated in the UK.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Europe has over 400 national parks, as of 2026.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The Vanoise National Park in the Alps was the first French national park, created in 1963 after public mobilization against a touristic project.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In 1973, Mount Kilimanjaro was classified as a National Park and was opened to public access in 1977.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In 1989, the Qomolangma National Nature Preserve (QNNP) was created to protect 3.381 million hectares on the north slope of Mount Everest in the Tibet Autonomous Region of China.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] This national park is the first major global park to have no separate warden and protection staff—all of its management consists of existing local authorities, allowing a lower cost basis and a larger geographical coverage (in 1989 when created, it was the largest protected area in Asia).
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] It includes four of the six tallest mountains in the world: Everest, Lhotse, Makalu, and Cho Oyu.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The QNNP is contiguous to four Nepali national parks, creating a transnational conservation area equal in size to Switzerland.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In 1993, the Blue and John Crow Mountains National Park was established in Jamaica to conserve and protect 41,198 hectares, including tropical montane rainforest and adjacent buffer areas.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The site includes Jamaica's tallest peak (Blue Mountain Peak), hiking trails and a visitor center.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The Park was also designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2015.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The world's first national park service was established May 19, 1911, in Canada.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The *Dominion Forest Reserves and Parks Act* placed the dominion parks under the administration of the Dominion Park Branch (now Parks Canada), within the Department of the Interior.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The branch was established to "protect sites of natural wonder" to provide a recreational experience, centred on the idea of the natural world providing rest and spiritual renewal from the urban setting.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Canada now has the largest protected area in the world with 450,000 km2 of national park space.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Even with the creation of Yellowstone, Yosemite, and nearly 37 other national parks and monuments, another 44 years passed before an agency was created in the United States to administer these units in a comprehensive way – the U.S.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The 64th United States Congress passed the National Park Service Organic Act, which President Woodrow Wilson signed into law on 25 August 1916.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Of the 433 sites managed by the National Park Service of the United States, only 63 carry the designation of National Park.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Countries with a large ecotourism industry, such as Costa Rica, often experience a huge economic effect on park management as well as the economy of the country as a whole.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Tourism to national parks has increased considerably over time.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In Costa Rica for example, a megadiverse country, tourism to parks has increased by 400% from 1985 to 1999.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The term *national park* is perceived as a brand name that is associated with nature-based tourism and it symbolizes a "high quality natural environment with a well-designed tourist infrastructure".
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] The duties of a park ranger are to supervise, manage, and/or perform work in the conservation and use of park resources.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] This involves functions such as park conservation; natural, historical, and cultural resource management; and the development and operation of interpretive and recreational programs for the benefit of the visiting public.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Park rangers also have fire fighting responsibilities and execute search and rescue missions.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Activities also include heritage interpretation to disseminate information to visitors of general, historical, or scientific information.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Management of resources such as wildlife, lake shores, seashores, forests, historic buildings, battlefields, archaeological properties, and recreation areas are also part of the job of a park ranger.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Since the establishment of the National Park Service in the US in 1916, the role of the park ranger has shifted from merely being a custodian of natural resources to include several activities that are associated with law enforcement.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] They control traffic, manage permits for various uses, and investigate violations, complaints, trespass/encroachment, and accidents.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] National parks in former European colonies have come under criticism for allegedly perpetuating colonialism.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] National parks were created by individuals who felt that pristine, natural sections of nature should be set aside and preserved from urban development.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] In America, this movement came about during the American frontier and were meant to be monuments to America's true history.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Yet, in some instances, the lands that were to be set aside and protected in formerly colonized lands were already being inhabited by native communities, who were then removed off of these lands to create pristine sites for public consumption.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Critics claim that the removal of people from national parks enhances the belief that nature can only be protected when humans do not exist within it, and that this leads to perpetuating the dichotomy between nature and humans (also known as the nature–culture divide).
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] They see the creation of national parks as a form of eco-land grabbing.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Others claim that traveling to national parks to appreciate nature there leads people to ignore the nature that exists around them every day.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Still others argue that tourism can actually negatively impact the areas that are being visited.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] Additionally, tourism in national parks can have negative environmental impacts.
[src:fire-safety-evaluation-system/national-park] High levels of visitation may lead to habitat degradation, pollution, soil erosion, and disturbances to wildlife, potentially undermining the ecological health of the areas the parks are intended to protect.
